1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,750
One of the questions I get asked most often about

2
00:00:09,050 --> 00:00:12,050
CueDeck is: does it work on a tablet?

3
00:00:12,350 --> 00:00:14,350
What about a phone?

4
00:00:14,650 --> 00:00:18,025
Can my stage manager use it on an iPad?

5
00:00:18,325 --> 00:00:20,575
The answer is yes — and

6
00:00:20,875 --> 00:00:25,000
in this episode I'll show you exactly what that looks like.

7
00:00:25,300 --> 00:00:27,550
CueDeck is a browser app, which

8
00:00:27,850 --> 00:00:31,600
means it runs on any device with a modern browser

9
00:00:31,900 --> 00:00:33,900
and an internet connection.

10
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:37,200
The layout adapts to the screen it's on.

11
00:00:37,500 --> 00:00:39,500
Let me show you how.

12
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:43,550
I'll use the browser's device emulation tools so you can

13
00:00:43,850 --> 00:00:45,850
see the responsive layout clearly.

14
00:00:46,150 --> 00:00:50,650
This is what CueDeck looks like on an iPad in portrait orientation.

15
00:00:50,950 --> 00:00:52,950
Notice what's changed.

16
00:00:53,250 --> 00:00:56,1000
The role bar — the strip of role buttons at

17
00:00:57,300 --> 00:01:01,050
the top — has wrapped onto two lines instead of

18
00:01:01,350 --> 00:01:03,350
trying to squeeze into one.

19
00:01:03,650 --> 00:01:07,775
The session list takes up the full width of the screen.

20
00:01:08,075 --> 00:01:11,825
The context panel, which on desktop sits to the right

21
00:01:12,125 --> 00:01:15,500
of the session list, moves to a sheet that

22
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:18,050
slides up from the bottom when

23
00:01:18,350 --> 00:01:20,350
you tap a session.

24
00:01:20,650 --> 00:01:23,650
On a tablet the interaction model is tap-first.

25
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:26,200
Tap a session to select it.

26
00:01:26,500 --> 00:01:28,500
The action sheet comes up.

27
00:01:28,800 --> 00:01:31,800
Tap the action button to trigger the transition.

28
00:01:32,100 --> 00:01:35,850
It works exactly the same as the desktop version —

29
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:39,150
just with your thumb instead of a mouse.

30
00:01:39,450 --> 00:01:42,450
The context panel sheet uses the same data,

31
00:01:42,750 --> 00:01:46,125
the same real-time sync, and the same state machine.

32
00:01:46,425 --> 00:01:48,675
Nothing is simplified or removed —

33
00:01:48,975 --> 00:01:50,975
it's the same production tool.

34
00:01:51,275 --> 00:01:56,150
Here's the setup I'd recommend for a stage manager running a single room.

35
00:01:56,450 --> 00:01:58,450
They're in Stage role.

36
00:01:58,750 --> 00:02:01,750
They have an iPad on a stand or

37
00:02:02,050 --> 00:02:04,675
a table just offstage — portrait orientation,

38
00:02:04,975 --> 00:02:06,975
tablet stand, screen always on.

39
00:02:07,275 --> 00:02:11,025
They can see the entire session list for their room

40
00:02:11,325 --> 00:02:15,075
— filter by room, and only their sessions are showing.

41
00:02:15,375 --> 00:02:18,375
When a speaker arrives they tap the session,

42
00:02:18,675 --> 00:02:21,675
tap Speaker Arrived, the director sees it immediately.

43
00:02:21,975 --> 00:02:24,600
When it's time to go live —

44
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:27,150
if the stage manager has that

45
00:02:27,450 --> 00:02:29,700
permission — one tap, one confirmation,

46
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
the session is live.

47
00:02:32,300 --> 00:02:34,300
No radio call needed.

48
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:38,350
The director sees it on their screen the same moment

49
00:02:38,650 --> 00:02:40,900
the stage manager taps the button.

50
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:44,575
The buttons are large enough for reliable touch input.

51
00:02:44,875 --> 00:02:49,750
There's no tiny click target that's easy to misfire when you're under pressure.

52
00:02:50,050 --> 00:02:53,800
The state machine still enforces all the same rules —

53
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:57,850
you can't accidentally put something LIVE that isn't READY first.

54
00:02:58,150 --> 00:03:00,775
Now let's look at a phone —

55
00:03:01,075 --> 00:03:03,700
this is the registration desk use case.

56
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,375
The Registration role has the simplest view in CueDeck:

57
00:03:07,675 --> 00:03:10,300
the upcoming session queue, who's on next,

58
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:13,975
and a read-only status of what's live right now.

59
00:03:14,275 --> 00:03:17,650
That's all the information a registration team needs —

60
00:03:17,950 --> 00:03:20,950
they're not running transitions, they're answering attendee questions.

61
00:03:21,250 --> 00:03:23,875
On a phone that view stacks cleanly.

62
00:03:24,175 --> 00:03:26,425
Session cards fill the full width,

63
00:03:26,725 --> 00:03:30,475
the current status badge is large enough to read at

64
00:03:30,775 --> 00:03:35,275
a glance, and the next session's speaker name and title are prominent.

65
00:03:35,575 --> 00:03:39,325
A registration team member can keep this open on their

66
00:03:39,625 --> 00:03:43,000
personal phone or a shared device at the desk,

67
00:03:43,300 --> 00:03:46,300
and the screen updates automatically without a refresh.

68
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:50,725
The moment the director takes a session LIVE, it appears here.

69
00:03:51,025 --> 00:03:53,025
No app to install.

70
00:03:53,325 --> 00:03:55,575
They sign in, pick their role,

71
00:03:55,875 --> 00:03:58,500
and the screen stays live all day.

72
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:02,550
For directors who run on a laptop with a tablet

73
00:04:02,850 --> 00:04:05,850
beside them — this is a useful configuration.

74
00:04:06,150 --> 00:04:08,400
The tablet is your second monitor.

75
00:04:08,700 --> 00:04:11,325
Open CueDeck in Safari on the iPad,

76
00:04:11,625 --> 00:04:13,875
keep it in landscape orientation, and

77
00:04:14,175 --> 00:04:17,925
you have the full director view with all controls available.

78
00:04:18,225 --> 00:04:21,975
Some directors I've spoken to use the tablet specifically for

79
00:04:22,275 --> 00:04:26,025
the signage panel — they keep their signage displays open

80
00:04:26,325 --> 00:04:30,075
on the iPad so they can monitor what's showing on

81
00:04:30,375 --> 00:04:33,750
the venue screens without switching windows on their laptop.

82
00:04:34,050 --> 00:04:36,300
Two views, one account, fully synced.

83
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:39,975
A few practical tips for mobile and tablet setups.

84
00:04:40,275 --> 00:04:42,525
First: use a dedicated browser tab,

85
00:04:42,825 --> 00:04:44,825
not a general browsing session.

86
00:04:45,125 --> 00:04:48,875
Keep CueDeck as its own pinned tab on the device.

87
00:04:49,175 --> 00:04:51,425
It's easier to find under pressure.

88
00:04:51,725 --> 00:04:55,475
Second: on iOS, you can add CueDeck to your Home

89
00:04:55,775 --> 00:04:59,150
Screen from Safari — tap the share button and

90
00:04:59,450 --> 00:05:01,450
choose 'Add to Home Screen'.

91
00:05:01,750 --> 00:05:05,500
It opens full-screen like a native app, no browser chrome.

92
00:05:05,800 --> 00:05:10,300
That's a cleaner experience on an iPad in portrait on a stand.

93
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:12,600
Third: keep the screen on.

94
00:05:12,900 --> 00:05:17,025
Most tablets dim the display after a minute of no interaction.

95
00:05:17,325 --> 00:05:19,575
Go into your device settings and

96
00:05:19,875 --> 00:05:22,500
set the screen timeout to 'Never' or

97
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:25,425
the longest available option for show day.

98
00:05:25,725 --> 00:05:30,225
You don't want the screen going dark while you're watching a speaker.

99
00:05:30,525 --> 00:05:32,525
Fourth: about internet connectivity.

100
00:05:32,825 --> 00:05:36,575
CueDeck requires an active internet connection for realtime sync —

101
00:05:36,875 --> 00:05:41,000
it's communicating with Supabase for every state change and every broadcast.

102
00:05:41,300 --> 00:05:44,675
If you're backstage at a venue with unreliable WiFi,

103
00:05:44,975 --> 00:05:47,600
test your connection before the event starts.

104
00:05:47,900 --> 00:05:52,775
A strong 4G signal on a mobile data connection is a reliable fallback.

105
00:05:53,075 --> 00:05:56,450
CueDeck works on any modern browser, on any device.

106
00:05:56,750 --> 00:06:00,500
The layout adapts, the touch targets are the right size,

107
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:04,175
and every role is usable on a phone or

108
00:06:04,475 --> 00:06:06,475
tablet without any feature degradation.

109
00:06:06,775 --> 00:06:09,775
For most production teams the sweet spot is:

110
00:06:10,075 --> 00:06:14,200
director on a laptop, stage managers on tablets, registration on phones.

111
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:18,250
Everyone connected, everyone synced, no one staring at a laptop

112
00:06:18,550 --> 00:06:21,550
screen when they should be watching the stage.

113
00:06:21,850 --> 00:06:24,100
Next episode is about billing —

114
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:28,150
the plans, the pricing, how the per-event credit option works,

115
00:06:28,450 --> 00:06:31,825
and how to upgrade when your team is ready.

116
00:06:32,125 --> 00:06:34,125
I'll see you there.
